result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Ruth A. Jenson

records.addlTxt:
Cases called at 9:15 AM: 21CF1400, 22CF172.
Defendant Ruth A. Jenson in court with Attorney Roger M Hillestad.  Attorney Angela Lynn Beranek in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Agreement has been reached. Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. 
Defendant pleads to Count 1: OWI 5th Offense. Defendant makes a statement to the Court.
Court sentences the Defendant to 1.5 Years of Initial Confinement followed by 3 Years of Extended Supervision.
Conditions of Extended Supervision: $600 Fine plus Costs and Blood Draw Fee.  36 Month DL Revocation, 36 Month IID.AODA and follow through with recommendations. 
Any conditions, programming or treatment per the agent and follow through with recommendations. Maintain absolute sobriety. 
Defendant is not granted any sentence credit. Court finds the Defendant is eligible for Substance Abuse Program but is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.Remaining charges are dismissed and read in.

10:10 AM Cases called: 21CF1400 & 22CF172 Prosecuting attorney Matthew Z Kirkpatrick in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Ruth A. Jenson in court.  Attorney Roger M Hillestad in court for Ruth A. Jenson. Defendant waives right to a preliminary hearing on both cases and Court accepts waiver. Refer to Br. 4 for scheduling.
